{"title_page": "Baron Methuen", "text_new": "{{short description|Title in the Peerage of the United Kingdom}}\n[[File:Paul Methuen, 3rd Baron Methuen.png|thumb|200px|Paul Methuen, 3rd Baron Methuen]]\n'''Baron Methuen''', of [[Corsham]] in the County of [[Wiltshire]], is a title in the [[Peerage of the United Kingdom]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=19629 |date=26 June 1838 |page=1445}}</ref> It was created in 1838 for the former [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wiltshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Wiltshire]] and [[Wiltshire North (UK Parliament constituency)|Wiltshire North]], [[Paul Methuen, 1st Baron Methuen|Paul Methuen]]. His grandson, the third Baron (who succeeded his father), was a distinguished soldier who became [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field marshal]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} His son, the fourth Baron, was a professional artist and Royal Academician. On his death the title passed to his younger brother, the fifth Baron.  The seventh Baron, who succeeded his elder brother in 1994, was one of the ninety [[hereditary peer]]s elected to the [[House of Lords]] after the passage of the [[House of Lords Act 1999]], and sat on the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] benches. {{As of|2014}}, the title is held by his first cousin once removed, the eighth baron, who succeeded to the title in that year.\n\nThe first Baron's grandfather, Paul Methuen, was the cousin and heir of the wealthy [[Paul Methuen (diplomat)|Sir Paul Methuen]], a well-known politician, courtier, diplomat and patron of art and literature, who was the son of [[John Methuen (diplomat)|John Methuen]] (c. 1650 \u2013 1706), [[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]] between 1697 and 1703 and [[List of Ambassadors from the United Kingdom to Portugal|ambassador]] to [[Portugal]]. It was the last-named who in 1703 negotiated the famous [[Methuen Treaty]], which, in return for the admission of English woollens into Portugal, granted differential duty favoring the importation of Portuguese wines into England to the disadvantage of French wines, and thus contributed to the replacement of the drinking of burgundy by that of [[port wine|port]].<ref name=EB1911>{{EB1911 |inline=1 |wstitle=Methuen, Barony of |volume=18 |page=298}}</ref>\n\nThe family seat is [[Corsham Court]], near [[Chippenham]], [[Wiltshire]].\n\n==Barons Methuen (1838)==\n[[File:CorshamCourtFront.jpg|thumb|240px|Corsham Court]]\n*[[Paul Methuen, 1st Baron Methuen]] (1779\u20131849)\n*[[Frederick Methuen, 2nd Baron Methuen|Frederick Henry Paul Methuen, 2nd Baron Methuen]] (1818\u20131891)\n*[[Paul Methuen, 3rd Baron Methuen|Paul Sanford Methuen, 3rd Baron Methuen]] (1845\u20131932)\n*[[Paul Ayshford Methuen, 4th Baron Methuen]] (1886\u20131974)\n*[[Anthony Methuen, 5th Baron Methuen|Anthony Paul Methuen, 5th Baron Methuen]] (1891\u20131975)\n*[[John Methuen, 6th Baron Methuen|(Anthony) John Methuen, 6th Baron Methuen]] (1925\u20131994)\n*[[Robert Methuen, 7th Baron Methuen|Robert Alexander Holt Methuen, 7th Baron Methuen]] (1931\u20132014)\n*[[James Methuen-Campbell, 8th Baron Methuen|James Paul Archibald Methuen-Campbell, 8th Baron Methuen]] (born 1952).\n\nThe [[heir presumptive]] is the present holder's half-brother, Thomas Rice Mansel Methuen-Campbell (born 1977).\n\n===Male-line family tree===\n{{chart top|width=100%|Male-line family tree, Barons Methuen.}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart|PM1B|PM1B='''[[Paul Methuen, 1st Baron Methuen|Paul Methuen<br>{{nowrap|1st Baron Methuen}}]]'''<br>1779\u20131849}}\n{{chart| |)|-|-|-|.| | }}\n{{chart|PM| |FM2B|PM=Paul Methuen<br>1814\u20131837|FM2B='''[[Frederick Methuen, 2nd Baron Methuen|Frederick Methuen<br>{{nowrap|2nd Baron Methuen}}]]'''<br>1818\u20131891}}\n{{chart| | | | | |!| | }}\n{{chart| | | | |PM3B|PM3B=Field Marshal<br>'''[[Paul Methuen, 3rd Baron Methuen|Paul Methuen<br>3rd Baron Methuen]]'''<br>1845\u20131932}}\n{{chart| | | | | |)|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|.| | }}\n{{chart| | | | |PM4B| |AM5B| | | | | | | | | |HLM|PM4B='''[[Paul Ayshford Methuen, 4th Baron Methuen|Paul Methuen<br>4th Baron Methuen]]'''<br>1886\u20131974|AM5B='''[[Anthony Methuen, 5th Baron Methuen|Anthony Methuen<br>{{nowrap|5th Baron Methuen}}]]'''<br>1891\u20131975|HLM=Hon.<br>Laurence Methuen<br>1898\u20131970}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | |)|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.| | | |!| | }}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | |AM| |JM6B| |RM7B| |CMC|AM=Anthony Methuen<br>1923\u20131934|JM6B='''[[John Methuen, 6th Baron Methuen|John Methuen<br>{{nowrap|6th Baron Methuen}}]]'''<br>1925\u20131994|RM7B='''[[Robert Methuen, 7th Baron Methuen|Robert Methuen<br>{{nowrap|7th Baron Methuen}}]]'''<br>1931\u20132014|CMC={{nowrap|Christopher Methuen-Campbell}}<br>1928\u20131998}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |)|-|-|-|.| | }}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |JMC8B| |TMC|JMC8B='''[[James Methuen-Campbell, 8th Baron Methuen|James Methuen-Campbell<br>8th Baron Methuen]]'''<br>born 1952|TMC={{nowrap|Thomas Methuen-Campbell}}<br>born 1977}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox emblem wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Methuen Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Argent three wolves\u2019 heads erased Proper on the breast of an eagle with two heads displayed Sable.\n|supporters = On either side two fiery lynxes reguardant Proper collared having a line passing between their forelegs reflexed over their backs Or.\n|motto = Virtus Invidiae Scopus <ref>{{cite book|title=Burke's Peerage |date=1959}}</ref>}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{refimprove|date=June 2014}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{Extant Barons of the United Kingdom}}\n\n==References==\n*Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990, {{Page needed |date=February 2013}}\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Methuen}}\n[[Category:Baronies in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1838 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Corsham]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Title in the Peerage of the United Kingdom}}\n[[File:Paul Methuen, 3rd Baron Methuen.png|thumb|200px|Paul Methuen, 3rd Baron Methuen]]\n'''Baron Methuen''', of [[Corsham]] in the County of [[Wiltshire]], is a title in the [[Peerage of the United Kingdom]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=19629 |date=26 June 1838 |page=1445}}</ref> It was created in 1838 for the former [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wiltshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Wiltshire]] and [[Wiltshire North (UK Parliament constituency)|Wiltshire North]], [[Paul Methuen, 1st Baron Methuen|Paul Methuen]]. His grandson, the third Baron (who succeeded his father), was a distinguished soldier who became [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field marshal]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} His son, the fourth Baron, was a professional artist and Royal Academician. On his death the title passed to his younger brother, the fifth Baron.  The seventh Baron, who succeeded his elder brother in 1994, was one of the ninety [[hereditary peer]]s elected to the [[House of Lords]] after the passage of the [[House of Lords Act 1999]], and sat on the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] benches. {{As of|2014}}, the title is held by his first cousin once removed, the eighth baron, who succeeded to the title in that year.\n\nThe first Baron's grandfather, Paul Methuen, was the cousin and heir of the wealthy [[Paul Methuen (diplomat)|Sir Paul Methuen]], a well-known politician, courtier, diplomat and patron of art and literature, who was the son of [[John Methuen (diplomat)|John Methuen]] (c. 1650 \u2013 1706), [[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]] between 1697 and 1703 and [[List of Ambassadors from the United Kingdom to Portugal|ambassador]] to [[Portugal]]. It was the last-named who in 1703 negotiated the famous [[Methuen Treaty]], which, in return for the admission of English woollens into Portugal, granted differential duty favoring the importation of Portuguese wines into England to the disadvantage of French wines, and thus contributed to the replacement of the drinking of burgundy by that of [[port wine|port]].<ref name=EB1911>{{EB1911 |inline=1 |wstitle=Methuen, Barony of |volume=18 |page=298}}</ref>\n\nThe family seat is [[Corsham Court]], near [[Chippenham]], [[Wiltshire]].\n\n==Barons Methuen (1838)==\n[[File:CorshamCourtFront.jpg|thumb|240px|Corsham Court]]\n*[[Paul Methuen, 1st Baron Methuen]] (1779\u20131849)\n*[[Frederick Methuen, 2nd Baron Methuen|Frederick Henry Paul Methuen, 2nd Baron Methuen]] (1818\u20131891)\n*[[Paul Methuen, 3rd Baron Methuen|Paul Sanford Methuen, 3rd Baron Methuen]] (1845\u20131932)\n*[[Paul Ayshford Methuen, 4th Baron Methuen]] (1886\u20131974)\n*[[Anthony Methuen, 5th Baron Methuen|Anthony Paul Methuen, 5th Baron Methuen]] (1891\u20131975)\n*[[John Methuen, 6th Baron Methuen|(Anthony) John Methuen, 6th Baron Methuen]] (1925\u20131994)\n*[[Robert Methuen, 7th Baron Methuen|Robert Alexander Holt Methuen, 7th Baron Methuen]] (1931\u20132014)\n*[[James Methuen-Campbell, 8th Baron Methuen|James Paul Archibald Methuen-Campbell, 8th Baron Methuen]] (born 1952).\n\nThe [[heir presumptive]] is the present holder's half-brother, Thomas Rice Mansel Methuen-Campbell (born 1977).\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Methuen Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Argent three wolves\u2019 heads erased Proper on the breast of an eagle with two heads displayed Sable.\n|supporters = On either side two fiery lynxes reguardant Proper collared having a line passing between their forelegs reflexed over their backs Or.\n|motto = Virtus Invidiae Scopus <ref>{{cite book|title=Burke's Peerage |date=1959}}</ref>}}\n\n==Male-line family tree==\n{{chart top|width=100%|Male-line family tree, Barons Methuen.}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart|PM1B|PM1B='''[[Paul Methuen, 1st Baron Methuen|Paul Methuen<br>{{nowrap|1st Baron Methuen}}]]'''<br>1779\u20131849}}\n{{chart| |)|-|-|-|.| | }}\n{{chart|PM| |FM2B|PM=Paul Methuen<br>1814\u20131837|FM2B='''[[Frederick Methuen, 2nd Baron Methuen|Frederick Methuen<br>{{nowrap|2nd Baron Methuen}}]]'''<br>1818\u20131891}}\n{{chart| | | | | |!| | }}\n{{chart| | | | |PM3B|PM3B=Field Marshal<br>'''[[Paul Methuen, 3rd Baron Methuen|Paul Methuen<br>3rd Baron Methuen]]'''<br>1845\u20131932}}\n{{chart| | | | | |)|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|.| | }}\n{{chart| | | | |PM4B| |AM5B| | | | | | | | | |HLM|PM4B='''[[Paul Ayshford Methuen, 4th Baron Methuen|Paul Methuen<br>4th Baron Methuen]]'''<br>1886\u20131974|AM5B='''[[Anthony Methuen, 5th Baron Methuen|Anthony Methuen<br>{{nowrap|5th Baron Methuen}}]]'''<br>1891\u20131975|HLM=Hon.<br>Laurence Methuen<br>1898\u20131970}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | |)|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.| | | |!| | }}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | |AM| |JM6B| |RM7B| |CMC|AM=Anthony Methuen<br>1923\u20131934|JM6B='''[[John Methuen, 6th Baron Methuen|John Methuen<br>{{nowrap|6th Baron Methuen}}]]'''<br>1925\u20131994|RM7B='''[[Robert Methuen, 7th Baron Methuen|Robert Methuen<br>{{nowrap|7th Baron Methuen}}]]'''<br>1931\u20132014|CMC={{nowrap|Christopher Methuen-Campbell}}<br>1928\u20131998}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |)|-|-|-|.| | }}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |JMC8B| |TMC|JMC8B='''[[James Methuen-Campbell, 8th Baron Methuen|James Methuen-Campbell<br>8th Baron Methuen]]'''<br>born 1952|TMC={{nowrap|Thomas Methuen-Campbell}}<br>born 1977}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{refimprove|date=June 2014}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{Extant Barons of the United Kingdom}}\n\n==References==\n*Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990, {{Page needed |date=February 2013}}\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Methuen}}\n[[Category:Baronies in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1838 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Corsham]]\n", "name_user": "HandsomeFella", "label": "safe", "comment": "reshuffle sections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baron_Methuen"}
{"title_page": "RAF Cranwell", "text_new": "{{about|the Royal Air Force station|the officer training establishment which lodges at RAF Cranwell|Royal Air Force College Cranwell}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = RAF Cranwell\n| ensign = Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg\n| ensign_size = 90px\n| native_name =\n| partof =\n| location =\n| nearest_town = [[Cranwell]], Lincolnshire\n| country = England\n| image =Graduates front of College Hall.jpg\n| caption =College Hall at [[Royal Air Force College Cranwell]]\n| image2 = RAF Cranwell.png\n| image2_size = 100px\n| caption2 = ''Alitum Altrix''<br>({{Language with name/for|2=Latin|3=''Nurture the Winged''}})<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pine|first1=L.G.|title=A dictionary of mottoes|date=1983|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|location=London|isbn=0-7100-9339-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofmott00tion/page/9 9]|edition=1|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofmott00tion/page/9}}</ref>\n| pushpin_map = Lincolnshire\n| pushpin_label = RAF Cranwell\n| pushpin_label_position = top\n| pushpin_map_caption = Shown within Lincolnshire\n| coordinates = {{Coord|53|01|49|N|000|29|00|W|region:GB_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| type = Training station\n| code =\n|site_area= {{convert|700|ha|acres}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/defence-estates-development-plan-dedp-2009|title=Defence Estates Development Plan 2009 \u2013 Annex A|date=3 July 2009|website=GOV.UK|publisher=Ministry of Defence|page=18|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 April 2019}}</ref>\n| height =\n| ownership = [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n| operator = [[Royal Air Force]]\n| controlledby = [[No. 22 Group RAF|No. 22 Group (Training)]]\n| open_to_public =\n| condition = Operational\n| built = {{Start date|1916}}\n| builder =\n| used = 1916\u20131918 ([[Royal Naval Air Service]])<br>1918 \u2013 present (Royal Air Force) <!--{{End date|1946}} -->\n| materials =\n| fate =\n| battles =\n| events =\n| current_commander = [[Air Commodore]] Suraya Marshall\n| past_commanders = <!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n| garrison =\n| occupants =\n* RAF College Cranwell\n* [[Central Flying School]]\n* [[No. 3 Flying Training School|HQ No. 3 Flying Training School]]\n* [[No. 45 Squadron RAF|No. 45 Squadron]]\n* [[No. 57 Squadron RAF|No. 57 Squadron]]\n* [[703 Naval Air Squadron|No. 703 Naval Air Squadron]] (operates from RAF Barkston Heath)\n* [[No. 674 Squadron AAC]] (operates from RAF Barkston Heath)\n* [[No. 6 Flying Training School|HQ No. 6 Flying Training School]]\n* [[University Air Squadron|East Midlands Universities Air Squadron]]\n* [[No. 7 Air Experience Flight RAF|No. 7 Air Experience Flight]]\n''See [[#Based units|Based units]] section for full list.''\n| elevation = {{Convert|67.7|m|0}}\n| IATA =\n| ICAO = EGYD\n| FAA =\n| TC =\n| LID =\n| GPS =\n| WMO = 03379\n| r1-number = 09/27\n| r1-length = {{Convert|2082|m|0}}\n| r1-surface = [[Asphalt]]/[[Concrete]]\n| r2-number = 01/19\n| r2-length = {{Convert|1462|m|0}}\n| r2-surface = Asphalt/Concrete\n| r3-number = 08N/26N\n| r3-length = {{Convert|761|m|0}}\n| r3-surface = Grass\n| r4-number = 08S/26S\n| r4-length = {{Convert|761|m|0}}\n| r4-surface = Grass\n| website = https://www.raf.mod.uk/rafcollegecranwell/\n|footnotes='''Source''': UK MIL AIP Cranwell<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aidu.mod.uk/aip/pdf/ad/EGYD-Cranwell-Combined.pdf|title=Cranwell AD 2 - EGYD - 1 - 1|date=28 March 2019|website=UK MIL AIP|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Royal Air Force Cranwell''' or more simply '''RAF Cranwell''' {{Airport codes||EGYD}} is a [[Royal Air Force]] [[Royal Air Force station|station]] in [[Lincolnshire]], England, close to the village of [[Cranwell]], near [[Sleaford]]. Among other functions, it is home to the [[RAF College Cranwell|Royal Air Force College]] (RAFC), which trains the RAF's new [[commissioned officer|officers]] and Aircrew. The motto, ''Altium Altrix'', meaning \"Nurture the highest\" appears above the main doors of the Officers Mess.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsnk.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/Heritage-Lincolnshire-Research.pdf|page=30|title=Ridges and Furrows|accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref> RAF Cranwell is currently commanded by Air Commodore Suraya Marshall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/|title=Royal Air Force|website=Royal Air Force|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|Royal Air Force College Cranwell}}\nThe history of military aviation at Cranwell goes back to November 1915,<ref name=AS2-74 >Halpenny (1981), p.74</ref> when the [[Admiralty]] requisitioned 2,500&nbsp;acres (10&nbsp;km\u00b2) of land from the [[Frederick Hervey, 4th Marquess of Bristol|Marquess of Bristol]]'s estate.<ref name=\"AS2-74\"/> And on 1 April 1916, the \"Royal Naval Air Service Training Establishment, Cranwell\" was officially born.<ref name=\"AS2-74\"/>\n\nIn 1917 a dedicated railway station was established for RAF Cranwell on a [[Cranwell branch|new single track branch line]] from Sleaford, the train being known as The Cranwell Flyer.<ref name = ludlam>A J Ludlam, ''The RAF Cranwell Railway'', Oakwood Press, Headington, 1988, {{ISBN|0 85361 379 6}}</ref>\n\nWith the establishment of the Royal Air Force as an independent service in 1918, the RNAS Training Establishment became RAF Cranwell.<ref name=AS2-75>Halpenny (1981), p.75</ref> The [[Royal Air Force College Cranwell]] was formed on 1 November 1919 as the RAF (Cadet) College.<ref>Phillips-Evans, J. ''The Longcrofts: 500 Years of a British Family'' (Amazon, 2012)</ref>\n\n==Role and operations==\n\n=== Royal Air Force College ===\nCranwell is home to the [[Royal Air Force College Cranwell|Royal Air Force College]] (RAFC), which trains the RAFs new [[commissioned officer|officers]] on a 24-week initial course, after which they are dispersed to their Phase II training for specific branch instruction. It is thus the RAF equivalent of [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|Sandhurst]] or the [[Britannia Royal Naval College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314222457/http://www.raf.mod.uk/rafcranwell/aboutus/oactu.cfm|title=OACTU|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== RAF Recruitment ===\nThe station is home to the [[Officer and Aircrew Selection Centre]] (OASC), where all applicants to the RAF as Officers or [[noncommissioned officer|non-commissioned]] [[aircrew]], are put through a 4-day rigorous selection process.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm198889/cmhansrd/1989-03-07/Writtens-6.html |publisher=Hansard  |title=Questions to Secretary of State on move to RAF Cranwell from RAF Biggin Hill|accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Headquarters Central Flying School===\nHQ CFS has been located at RAF Cranwell since 1995 when it moved from [[RAF Scampton]]. The Central Flying School currently trains all RAF [[Qualified Flying Instructor|QFI]] flying instructors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080320115847/http://www.raf.mod.uk/rafcranwell/aboutus/cfs.cfm|title=Central Flying School|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== No. 3 Flying Training School ===\nCranwell is home to the headquarters of [[No. 3 Flying Training School RAF|No. 3 Flying Training School]] (No. 3 FTS). The school provides elementary flying training for fixed wing and multi-engine student pilots from the RAF, [[Fleet Air Arm]] and [[Army Air Corps (United Kingdom)|Army Air Corps]] through [[No. 57 Squadron RAF|No. 57 (Reserve) Squadron]], [[703 Naval Air Squadron|No. 703 Naval Air Squadron]] and [[No. 674 Squadron AAC|No. 674 Squadron Army Air Corps]]. The [[UK Military Flying Training System]] (UKMFTS) operates the [[Grob G 120TP|Grob Prefect T1]] in this role. Although nominally based at Cranwell, elementary training largely takes place at nearby [[RAF Barkston Heath]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raf-beta-public.org/aircraft/120tp-prefect/|title=120TP Prefect|website=Royal Air Force (Beta)|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 February 2018}}</ref> After elementary training, aircrews streamed to fly multi-engine aircraft and rear-seat roles are trained by [[No. 45 Squadron RAF|No. 45(R) Squadron]], which operate five [[Embraer Phenom 100]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/|title=Royal Air Force|website=Royal Air Force|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 January 2018, the Skyes Building was opened at Cranwell by [[Sean Reynolds (RAF officer)|Air Marshal Sean Reynolds]], the Deputy Commander Capability and Senior Responsible Owner of the UKMFTS. The building acts as a UKMFTS operational support building and be used to train new RAF pilots. It was named after [[Frederick Sykes|Air-Vice Marshal Sir Frederick Hugh Sykes]], a British military officer and politician who served during the [[World War I|First World War]].<ref>{{Cite journal|date=February 2018|title=Cutting-edge milestone for UKMFTS programme|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/678953/desider_115_Feb2018-Web.pdf|journal=desider|publisher=Ministry of Defence / Defence Equipment & Support|volume=115|pages=12}}</ref>\n\n=== Air Cadets ===\nSince the mid-1990s, Cranwell has been home to Headquarters, [[Air Training Corps|Air Cadets]], and the [[Air Cadet Organisation]]'s Adult Training Facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/aircadets/who-we-are/contact-us/|title=HQ Air Cadets|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Based units ==\n[[File:45 (R) Squadron, Embraer Phenom 100 MOD 45164824.jpg|alt=|thumb|An Embraer [[Embraer Phenom 100|Phenom 100]], operated by [[No. 45 Squadron RAF|No. 45 Squadron]]'s based at RAF Cranwell]]\nThe following notable flying and non-flying units are based at RAF Cranwell.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/our-organisation/stations/raf-college-cranwell/|title=RAF College Cranwell - Who's Based Here|website=Royal Air Force|language=en-gb|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Royal Air Force ===\n*[[No. 22 Group RAF|No. 22 Group (Training) RAF]]\n** RAF College Cranwell\n*** Officer and Aircrew Cadet Training Unit (OACTU)\n***Recruiting and Selection\n***Tedder Academy\n** [[Defence College of Aeronautical Engineering|Defence College of Aeronautical Engineering (DCAE)]]\n***Officer Training\n** [[Central Flying School]]\n*** Central Flying School Headquarters \n** [[No. 3 Flying Training School RAF|No. 3 Flying Training School]]\n*** No. 3 Flying Training School Headquarters\n*** [[No. 45 Squadron RAF|No. 45 Squadron]] \u2013 [[Embraer Phenom 100|Embraer Phenom T1]]\n*** [[No. 57 Squadron RAF|No. 57 Squadron]] \u2013 [[Grob G 120TP|Grob Prefect T1]]\n** [[No. 6 Flying Training School RAF|No. 6 Flying Training School]]\n*** No. 6 Flying Training School Headquarters\n*** [[University Air Squadron|East Midlands Universities Air Squadron]] \u2013 Grob Tutor T1\n*** [[No. 7 Air Experience Flight RAF|No. 7 Air Experience Flight]] \u2013 Grob Tutor T1\n*[[Air Training Corps]] Headquarters\n*[[No. 2 Group RAF|No. 2 Group (Air Combat Support) RAF]]\n**[[RAF Force Protection Force Headquarters|No. 8 RAF Force Protection Wing]]\n*** No. 5 [[Royal Air Force Police|RAF Police]] Squadron\n*** RAF Police [[Special Investigation Branch|Specialist Investigations Branch]] (North)\n*[[No. 38 Group RAF|No. 38 Group (Air Combat Service Support) RAF]]\n** [[Royal Air Force Music Services|RAF Music Services]]\n*** The Band of the Royal Air Force College\n*** The Band of the Royal Auxiliary Air Force\n*[[Air Warfare Centre|RAF Air Warfare Centre]]\n**Air Warfare School\n*Other RAF Units\n**RAF Disclosures\n\n=== Civilian ===\n* RAF Cranwell Flying Club\n* Cranwell Gliding Club\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Royal Air Force stations]]\n*[[Cranwell Light Aeroplane Club]]\n*[[RAF Harlaxton]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* [[Bruce Barrymore Halpenny|Halpenny, Bruce Barrymore]]. 1981. Action Stations Vol.2: Wartime Military Airfields of Lincolnshire and the East Midlands {{ISBN|978-1-85260-405-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|RAF Cranwell}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.raf.mod.uk/our-organisation/stations/raf-college-cranwell/}}\n*[http://forcespublishing.co.uk/pages/raf_publications_pages/raf_cranwell.html Cranwell Courier] \u2013 RAF Cranwell station magazine\n*[https://www.cranwellgc.co.uk/ Cranwell Gliding Club]\n\n{{Royal Air Force}}\n{{RAF stations in Lincolnshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cranwell}}\n[[Category:Royal Air Force stations in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Airports in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Royal Air Force station|the officer training establishment which lodges at RAF Cranwell|Royal Air Force College Cranwell}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = RAF Cranwell\n| ensign = Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg\n| ensign_size = 90px\n| native_name =\n| partof =\n| location =\n| nearest_town = [[Cranwell]], Lincolnshire\n| country = England\n| image =Graduates front of College Hall.jpg\n| caption =College Hall at [[Royal Air Force College Cranwell]]\n| image2 = RAF Cranwell.png\n| image2_size = 100px\n| caption2 = ''Alitum Altrix''<br>({{Language with name/for|2=Latin|3=''Nurture the Winged''}})<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pine|first1=L.G.|title=A dictionary of mottoes|date=1983|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|location=London|isbn=0-7100-9339-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofmott00tion/page/9 9]|edition=1|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofmott00tion/page/9}}</ref>\n| pushpin_map = Lincolnshire\n| pushpin_label = RAF Cranwell\n| pushpin_label_position = top